233
00:20:13,209 --> 00:20:15,894
You don't say. Ordnungsdienst.

234
00:20:15,990 --> 00:20:18,387
I'm a policeman now,
could you believe it?
It's hard to believe.

235
00:20:18,483 --> 00:20:20,399
Oh, no,
it's not hard
to believe.

236
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:22,800
It's a good racket, Poldek.
The only racket here.

237
00:20:22,801 --> 00:20:26,155
Look, maybe I could
put in a good word for you
with my superiors.

238
00:20:26,156 --> 00:20:30,280
Your superiors?
Come on, they are not
as bad as everyone says.

239
00:20:30,376 --> 00:20:33,445
Well, they're worse
than everyone says,
but it's a lot of money.

240
00:20:33,540 --> 00:20:36,034
A lot of money.

241
00:20:36,131 --> 00:20:38,720
Give me my housing assignment.

242
00:20:38,815 --> 00:20:43,036
Come on.
You look funny
in that hat, Goldberg.

243
00:20:43,131 --> 00:20:46,392
You look like a clown,
you know?

244
00:20:51,187 --> 00:20:53,488
He's a very important man.

245
00:20:53,489 --> 00:20:55,215
Just give him
two minutes of your time.

246
00:20:55,312 --> 00:20:58,572
Since when did time cost money?
Just sit down and listen.

247
00:20:58,668 --> 00:21:00,778
Please. Sir?

248
00:21:04,327 --> 00:21:06,341
For each thousand you invest,
I will repay you with...

249
00:21:06,342 --> 00:21:08,451
Two hundred.
200 kilos
of enamelware a month,

250
00:21:08,546 --> 00:21:10,368
to begin in July
and to continue
for one year.

251
00:21:10,465 --> 00:21:14,109
After which time, we're even.
That's it. It's very simple.

252
00:21:14,110 --> 00:21:16,985
Not good enough.
It's not
good enough.

253
00:21:16,986 --> 00:21:19,193
Not good enough?

254
00:21:19,288 --> 00:21:23,220
Look where you're living.
Look where you've been put.
"Not good enough."

255
00:21:23,317 --> 00:21:25,714
A couple of months ago you'd
be right, not anymore.

256
00:21:25,809 --> 00:21:28,782
Money's still money.

257
00:21:30,317 --> 00:21:32,523
No, it is not.

258
00:21:32,524 --> 00:21:34,537
That's why we're here.

259
00:21:34,633 --> 00:21:36,549
Trade goods--
that's the only currency...

260
00:21:36,550 --> 00:21:38,469
that'll be worth
anything in the ghetto.

261
00:21:38,470 --> 00:21:41,731
Things have changed, my friend.

262
00:21:42,498 --> 00:21:44,799
Did I call this meeting?

263
00:21:44,895 --> 00:21:47,196
You told Mr. Stern
you wanted to speak to me.

264
00:21:47,293 --> 00:21:49,786
I'm here.
I've made you a fair offer.

265
00:21:49,787 --> 00:21:53,622
Fair would be
a percentage in the company.

266
00:21:53,719 --> 00:21:56,787
Forget the whole thing.

267
00:21:56,883 --> 00:21:59,089
Get out.

268
00:22:03,118 --> 00:22:06,089
How do we know that you
will do what you say?

269
00:22:06,090 --> 00:22:08,008
Because I said I would.

270
00:22:08,009 --> 00:22:10,214
You want a contract?
To be upheld by what court?

271
00:22:10,215 --> 00:22:13,091
I said what I'll do.
That's our contract.

272
00:22:16,352 --> 00:22:18,462
...mielismy racje.

273
00:22:29,683 --> 00:22:34,862
Piec, szesc, siedem...

274
00:22:34,958 --> 00:22:38,411
osiem, dziewiec.

275
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:53,563
The standard SS rate for
Jewish skilled labor
is seven marks a day,

276
00:22:53,564 --> 00:22:56,441
five for unskilled and women.

277
00:22:56,538 --> 00:22:59,414
This is what you pay
the Reich Economic Office.

278
00:22:59,511 --> 00:23:01,908
TheJews themselves
receive nothing.

279
00:23:02,003 --> 00:23:06,224
Poles you pay wages.
Generally, they get
a little more.

280
00:23:06,320 --> 00:23:08,813
Are you
listening?
What was that about the SS?

281
00:23:08,909 --> 00:23:11,020
The rate? The what?

282
00:23:11,115 --> 00:23:14,568
TheJewish worker's salary--
you pay it directly to
the SS, not to the worker.

283
00:23:14,663 --> 00:23:16,676
He gets nothing. But it's less.

284
00:23:16,677 --> 00:23:18,692
It's less than what
I would pay a Pole.
It's less.

285
00:23:18,787 --> 00:23:21,568
That's the point
I'm trying to make.

286
00:23:21,665 --> 00:23:24,159
Poles cost more.

287
00:23:24,254 --> 00:23:28,666
Why should I hire Poles?

288
00:23:28,762 --> 00:23:32,502
An enamelware factory
over at, uh, Lipowa Street.

289
00:23:32,598 --> 00:23:35,379
It, uh, it, um--
It's owned by a German.

290
00:23:35,475 --> 00:23:38,448
But it's outside
the ghetto, so you can
barter for extra goods--

291
00:23:38,449 --> 00:23:40,654
for eggs, I don't know
what you need--

292
00:23:40,750 --> 00:23:42,764
with the Polish workers.
You can't get it here.

293
00:23:42,765 --> 00:23:46,888
Also, he's asking for ten
healthy women for the--
I am healthy.

294
00:23:46,984 --> 00:23:49,861
Bring your sister, okay?

295
00:23:53,985 --> 00:23:56,287
Chodz.

296
00:23:56,383 --> 00:23:59,644
You need to convince them
you have a trade, something
valuable to the war effort.

297
00:23:59,739 --> 00:24:01,849
Like what?
What if you don't?
I'm a musician.

298
00:24:01,946 --> 00:24:05,398
Your name goes
on a list.
And they put you on trucks--

299
00:24:05,494 --> 00:24:07,508
No, no, no,
that's not true.
You're a musician?

300
00:24:07,603 --> 00:24:10,002
Yeah.
I'd fid a good
hiding place if I were you.

301
00:24:10,097 --> 00:24:14,412
I'm not going to hide
like some animal.
There are places to hide.

302
00:24:18,825 --> 00:24:20,647
Der Naechste.!

303
00:24:20,744 --> 00:24:24,003
I'm a graduate
of the University of Lwow.

304
00:24:24,004 --> 00:24:27,170
I used to work at the
hydroelectric station
in Roznow--

305
00:24:27,265 --> 00:24:29,087
Blauschein.

306
00:24:32,252 --> 00:24:35,993
I'm gonna get the necessary
papers because this card
is no good anymore.

307
00:24:36,088 --> 00:24:38,390
You can stay in this line
all day, you'll still get
one of these.

308
00:24:38,486 --> 00:24:42,034
They are no good.
You'll have to leave
the line now,

309
00:24:42,131 --> 00:24:46,542
then you'll get a blue card,
a Blauschein, to say that
you are an essential worker.

310
00:24:46,638 --> 00:24:49,610
I'll get these papers
for you at Pankiewicz.

311
00:24:49,611 --> 00:24:51,529
Pharmacist. Just there, look.

312
00:24:51,625 --> 00:24:53,448
Guess who is here?

313
00:24:53,543 --> 00:24:56,132
Poldek! Enjoying
the weather, Poldek?

314
00:24:56,229 --> 00:24:59,105
Enjoying the lines?
Need some shoe polish?

315
00:24:59,106 --> 00:25:01,599
In a metal container maybe?

316
00:25:01,600 --> 00:25:05,915
Not essential?
I think you misunderstand
the meaning of the word.

317
00:25:06,011 --> 00:25:08,792
No Blauschein, sir.
Stand over there.

318
00:25:08,889 --> 00:25:11,573
Move. Next!

319
00:25:11,670 --> 00:25:13,780
What do you mean,
"Not essential"?

320
00:25:13,875 --> 00:25:19,342
I teach history and literature.
Since when is not essential?

321
00:25:24,425 --> 00:25:26,727
He's a metal polisher.

322
00:25:33,344 --> 00:25:36,030
It was not right?
It's very good.
He's 53 years old.

323
00:25:36,126 --> 00:25:39,099
It's too new. Mmm. Thank you.

324
00:25:46,963 --> 00:25:49,360
You're crazy.
You left it
in your drawer.

325
00:25:49,361 --> 00:25:51,566
How many times have I told you?

326
00:25:51,663 --> 00:25:54,252
Your work certificate
you keep in your pocket
at all times.

327
00:25:54,348 --> 00:25:56,170
And you leave everything
in your drawer.

328
00:25:56,267 --> 00:25:58,568
How many times I've told you?

329
00:25:58,664 --> 00:26:01,732
I'm a metal polisher.

330
00:26:10,173 --> 00:26:12,666
Take the round sheet of tin,

331
00:26:12,762 --> 00:26:16,503
dip it in soap emulsion.

332
00:26:16,598 --> 00:26:21,489
Then place it centrally
in the press.

333
00:26:36,068 --> 00:26:39,328
We obtain the soup pot.
The soup pot.

334
00:26:39,424 --> 00:26:42,684
Soup pot.

335
00:26:42,781 --> 00:26:45,754
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz,
stay together.

336
00:26:49,878 --> 00:26:54,864
Sir, I have ten work permits
here for the Deutsche
Emailwarenfabrik,

337
00:26:54,865 --> 00:26:57,645
cosigned by Mr. Bankier
and myself.

338
00:26:57,646 --> 00:27:02,154
If it's carbonized,
clean it with a file.

339
00:27:02,249 --> 00:27:06,852
But don't touch
both the electrodes
at the same time.

340
00:27:06,853 --> 00:27:09,923
You'll get electrocuted.
Here, have a try.

341
00:27:14,142 --> 00:27:16,444
Roll the metal under the press,

342
00:27:16,539 --> 00:27:18,841
but be very careful
unless you want your fingers...

343
00:27:18,938 --> 00:27:21,623
to become part of the teapot.

344
00:27:23,157 --> 00:27:26,705
Occupation?
I'm a writer.
I play the flute.

345
00:27:26,706 --> 00:27:30,061
But Moses is
a skilled metalworker.

346
00:27:30,062 --> 00:27:32,269
He can make tin pots.
He can make tanks.

347
00:27:32,364 --> 00:27:34,187
He can make whatever
Mr. Schindler asks.

348
00:27:34,283 --> 00:27:36,775
He's highly skilled.
Give him your card.

349
00:27:36,776 --> 00:27:39,077
Moses, give him your card.

350
00:27:41,092 --> 00:27:43,298
Now, dip the basin
with the tongs...

351
00:27:43,394 --> 00:27:45,792
into the enamel solution.

352
00:27:47,805 --> 00:27:52,026
And after swiveling it around,
carefully place it aside
to drip dry.

353
00:27:54,902 --> 00:27:58,260
And whatever he asks you,
allow me just to represent
you and speak for you.

354
00:27:58,355 --> 00:28:00,274
Don't say a word.

355
00:28:00,369 --> 00:28:03,726
Filing, billing, keeping track
of my appointments, shorthand.

356
00:28:03,727 --> 00:28:07,849
Typing, obviously.
How is your typing?
Uh, all right.

357
00:28:07,946 --> 00:28:09,768
Please.

358
00:29:00,502 --> 00:29:04,051
You need a secretary. Pick one.

359
00:29:04,052 --> 00:29:08,845
I don't know how.
They're all so...
qualified.

360
00:29:08,846 --> 00:29:11,723
You have to choose.

361
00:29:13,930 --> 00:29:16,614
Prosze sie ladnie usmiechac.
Big smile.
Big smile.

362
00:29:16,615 --> 00:29:18,053
Uwaga.

363
00:29:22,082 --> 00:29:24,191
# ###

364
00:29:36,756 --> 00:29:39,537
If you would,
look after my guest.

365
00:29:39,632 --> 00:29:44,714
Um, boxed teas are good.
Coffiee, pate, um...

366
00:29:44,715 --> 00:29:48,744
kielbasa sausage,
cheeses, Beluga caviar.
Yes.

367
00:29:48,839 --> 00:29:50,566
And, of course, who could live
without German cigarettes?

368
00:29:50,662 --> 00:29:52,771
Get me as many as you can fid.

369
00:29:52,868 --> 00:29:54,882
And some more fresh fruit.

370
00:29:54,978 --> 00:29:57,662
The real rarities--
oranges, lemons, pineapples.

371
00:29:57,663 --> 00:30:00,347
I need several boxes
of Cuban cigars. The best.
Yes.

372
00:30:00,348 --> 00:30:03,993
And dark, unsweetened chocolate.
Not in the shape ofladyfigers,
the chunk chocolate.

373
00:30:04,089 --> 00:30:07,061
Yes.
Big as my hand,
you sample at wine tastings.

374
00:30:07,158 --> 00:30:10,226
We're going to need lots
of cognac. The best, Hennessy.

375
00:30:10,323 --> 00:30:15,501
Dom Perignon champagne.
Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

376
00:30:15,598 --> 00:30:18,475
and, oh,
try to fid nylon stockings.

377
00:30:20,872 --> 00:30:23,942
It is my distinct pleasure
to announce...

378
00:30:24,037 --> 00:30:29,408
the fully operational status
of Deutsche Email Fabrik...

379
00:30:29,504 --> 00:30:30,750
Patrzjakies szmaty.!

380
00:30:30,751 --> 00:30:34,106
Manufacturers of superior
enamelware crockery...

381
00:30:34,107 --> 00:30:39,381
expressly designed
and crafted for military use.

382
00:30:39,382 --> 00:30:41,972
Utilizing only
the most modern equipment,

383
00:30:42,068 --> 00:30:46,958
D.E.F. 's staff I of
highly-skilled and experienced
artisans andjourneymen...

384
00:30:46,959 --> 00:30:50,412
deliver a product
of unparalleled quality,

385
00:30:50,507 --> 00:30:54,248
enabling me to proffier,
with absolute confidence
and pride,

386
00:30:54,344 --> 00:30:56,838
a full line
of field and kitchenware...

387
00:30:56,933 --> 00:31:00,865
unsurpassable in all respects
by my competitors.

388
00:31:00,962 --> 00:31:03,455
See attached list
and available colors.

389
00:31:03,551 --> 00:31:08,154
Anticipating the enclosed bids
will meet with your approval.

390
00:31:08,250 --> 00:31:11,894
Made in Havana, Cuba.
Looking forward to a long and
mutually prosperous association.

391
00:31:11,991 --> 00:31:15,060
Look at this.
I extend to you in advance
my sincerest gratitude...

392
00:31:15,155 --> 00:31:17,936
and very best regards.
Oskar Schindler.

393
00:31:18,033 --> 00:31:21,293
Yeah, I need 700 gross
from here for next Thursday.

394
00:31:21,389 --> 00:31:24,074
Nine hundred--
No, make it ten
for Wednesday.

395
00:31:24,075 --> 00:31:27,815
All this stuff here goes
to Madritsch's factory
on Tuesday of next week.

396
00:31:42,968 --> 00:31:46,229
My father was fond of saying,
"You need three things in life

397
00:31:46,325 --> 00:31:50,257
"a good doctor,
a forgiving priest...

398
00:31:50,353 --> 00:31:53,423
and a clever accountant."

399
00:31:56,683 --> 00:32:00,615
The first two...
I've never had much use for.

400
00:32:00,711 --> 00:32:03,971
But the third--

401
00:32:09,055 --> 00:32:12,411
Just pretend,
for Christ's sake.

402
00:32:15,961 --> 00:32:19,029
Is that all?

403
00:32:23,633 --> 00:32:26,701
I'm trying to thank you.

404
00:32:26,798 --> 00:32:30,825
I'm saying I couldn't
have done this without you.

405
00:32:33,224 --> 00:32:36,005
The usual thing would be
to acknowledge my gratitude.

406
00:32:36,100 --> 00:32:40,800
It would also, by the way,
be the courteous thing.

407
00:32:40,801 --> 00:32:43,582
You're welcome.

408
00:32:52,117 --> 00:32:54,227
Get out of here.

409
00:33:07,079 --> 00:33:10,147
Klonowska, who is it?

410
00:33:19,067 --> 00:33:21,656
She's so embarrassed.
Look at her.

411
00:33:33,165 --> 00:33:35,371
You know something?
You would like her.

412
00:33:35,467 --> 00:33:37,289
Oskar, please. What?

413
00:33:37,384 --> 00:33:39,686
I don't have to like her...
just because you do.
You would, though.

414
00:33:39,783 --> 00:33:42,467
It doesn't work that way.

415
00:33:54,648 --> 00:33:57,429
You've done well here.

416
00:33:59,732 --> 00:34:02,224
You look wonderful.

417
00:34:05,005 --> 00:34:08,363
Be careful
of the step, miss.
Mrs. Schindler, Marek.

418
00:34:14,884 --> 00:34:20,447
# #

419
00:34:20,543 --> 00:34:24,378
It's not a charade,
all this?
How could it

420
00:34:24,379 --> 00:34:26,777
The clothes, the car,
the apartment.
Wait a minute.

421
00:34:26,778 --> 00:34:30,612
Take a guess how many
people are on my payroll.
Oskar.

422
00:34:30,613 --> 00:34:36,175
My father, at the height
of his success, had 50.
I've got 350.

423
00:34:36,176 --> 00:34:40,300
350 workers
on the factory floor,
with one purpose.

424
00:34:40,395 --> 00:34:42,505
To make pots and pans?

425
00:34:42,602 --> 00:34:46,436
To make money. For me.

426
00:34:51,904 --> 00:34:54,974
Does anyone ask about me?

427
00:34:56,412 --> 00:34:59,481
Back home? Everybody.

428
00:34:59,577 --> 00:35:02,358
All the time.

429
00:35:02,454 --> 00:35:05,618
Hmm.

430
00:35:05,619 --> 00:35:10,989
They won't soon forget
the name Schindler here,
I can tell you that.

431
00:35:12,428 --> 00:35:15,498
"Oskar Schindler," they'll say.

432
00:35:15,593 --> 00:35:18,854
"Everybody remembers him.

433
00:35:18,950 --> 00:35:23,170
"He did something
extraordinary.

434
00:35:23,265 --> 00:35:28,157
"He did something
no one else did.

435
00:35:28,253 --> 00:35:31,418
"He came here with nothing--

436
00:35:31,513 --> 00:35:34,294
"a suitcase--

437
00:35:34,391 --> 00:35:39,760
"and built a bankrupt
company into a major
manufactory.

438
00:35:39,761 --> 00:35:43,214
"And left with
a steamer trunk--

439
00:35:43,311 --> 00:35:47,722
"Two steamer trunks
full of money,

440
00:35:47,818 --> 00:35:51,941
all the riches of the world."

441
00:35:51,942 --> 00:35:53,858
Hmm.

442
00:35:53,859 --> 00:35:57,025
It's comforting to see
that nothing's changed.

443
00:35:57,121 --> 00:36:00,573
You're wrong, Emilie.

444
00:36:00,574 --> 00:36:02,970
There's no way I could have
known this before,

445
00:36:02,971 --> 00:36:06,327
but there was always
something missing.

446
00:36:06,328 --> 00:36:10,260
In every business I tried,
I can see now, it wasn't me
that failed.

447
00:36:10,356 --> 00:36:13,040
Something was missing.

448
00:36:13,041 --> 00:36:16,494
Even if I'd known what it
was, there's nothing I could
have done about it...

449
00:36:16,589 --> 00:36:21,001
because you can't
create this thing.

450
00:36:21,098 --> 00:36:26,179
And it makes all
the difference in the world
between success and failure.

451
00:36:26,180 --> 00:36:28,674
Luck?

452
00:36:30,976 --> 00:36:33,757
War.

453
00:36:56,295 --> 00:36:59,843
Should I stay?

454
00:36:59,940 --> 00:37:04,542
It's a beautiful city.

455
00:37:04,543 --> 00:37:09,337
I asked you if I should stay.

456
00:37:09,338 --> 00:37:12,311
It's up to you.

457
00:37:16,052 --> 00:37:20,464
Promise me, Oskar,
no doorman or maitre d'
will ever presume...

458
00:37:20,559 --> 00:37:25,739
I'm anyone other
than Mrs. Schindler,
and I'll stay.

459
00:37:27,848 --> 00:37:30,054
Good-bye, darling.

460
00:37:45,975 --> 00:37:50,003
I could try to read this
or I could eat my lunch
while it's still hot.

461
00:37:50,099 --> 00:37:52,017
We're doing well?

462
00:37:52,112 --> 00:37:53,263
Yes.
Better this month
than last?

463
00:37:53,360 --> 00:37:55,564
Yes.
Any reason
to think next month

464
00:37:55,565 --> 00:37:58,730
The war could end.

465
00:38:08,225 --> 00:38:10,717
What?
There is a machinist
outside...

466
00:38:10,718 --> 00:38:13,692
who'd like to thank you
personally for giving him a job.

467
00:38:13,787 --> 00:38:18,295
Every day he comes.
He's very grateful.
It'll just take a minute.

468
00:38:24,337 --> 00:38:26,639
Mr. Lowenstein?

